label: PAN
description:
Cult far east club assassin Tzusing galvanises cyber-industrial and EBM with cinematic sound design in a raving meditation on masculinity for PAN, following a decade of building the fiercest reputation via productions on L.I.E.S. and powerful DJ sets.

‘绿帽 Green Hat’ is the 2nd album of strapping club music and computer game-like SFX by Malay born, Taiwan-based artist Tzusing. The dozen tracks feature scything, pulsating rhythms and gnashing electronics influenced as much by Tzusing’s... more

label: Brunette Editions
description:
One of ‘00s minimalism’s most enduring artists, John Roberts pursues his mmml deep house and post-classical muses farther into experimental interzones on his first album since 2019

Part responsible for steering minimal house somewhere more intriguing by the end of the ‘00s, NYC’s John Roberts has remained inquisitive at the edges of styles in a manner comparable with scene peers such as Nico Jaar and Lawrence over the past decade. ‘Wrecked Exotic’ follows from Roberts’ 2019... more

label: DECISIONS
description:
Air Max 97 catches the hard techno buzz on a hardworking trio for his home-brewed label, Decisions

Better known for twisting his rhythms off the bone for the past decade, AM97 here reads the room’s need for pounding momentum in two steely aces on the ‘Enthusiast’ EP, sandwiching a more typical cut of syncopated electro-grime freakiness.

His title tune hits hard at 148bpm with punishing acid/dark psy-trance momentum offset by hardstyle-d vamps and whipsmart edits. ‘Carbon’... more

label: Nervous Horizon
description:
Snarling raggo-tek on TSVI & Wallwork’s hard drum temple, Nervous Horizon 

Chasing up tuff turns on Textonic and Snaker Social Club, London’s Cocktail Party Effect cuts thru the noise with a handful of pugilistic club steppers and brawlers. Charred bass drum are fired off in the brusque tattoo of ‘Fixing The Roof’, and ‘Safety Button’ drops worm-charming subs in a buckled, underwater dancehall-techno style. ‘767’ tilts recklessly into breakcore-jungle ballistics with throat-slitting breakbeat... more

label: KECK
description:
Giant Swan's club-oriented 5-track EP, Fantasy Food.

"Featuring all chopped up voices, echoing kicks and k-hole synth lines, this EP follows on from the Do Not Be Afriad Of Tenderness EP in early 2021, and the self-titled debut album that preceded it. 

A duo consisting of Robin Stewart and Harry Wright, Giant Swan are one of the most exciting artists to emerge from the UK underground in recent years. With equal appeal to fans of hardcore punk or noise-rock as club kids and clued up... more

label: Timedance
description:
UK techno disruptor Metrist metes out a 3rd EP of itchy, offbeat club music for Batu’s label

Hitting the mark somewhere between the corkscrewing rhythms of his label boss and the misshapen structures of Blawan, or Happa’s unpredictable arrangements, Metrist trades in deep fried freakiness on all six cuts of ‘Pollen, Pt. III’.

Vocals are a crucial ingredient here, found most rudely on the squashed slug of ‘Bullet Time’ stalked by Older Brother, and more obliquely in the strobing, cut-up phonemes... more

title_full:
Peder Mannerfelt

              —
              The Benefits of Living in a Hole

label: Voam
description:
Back to bang on Blawan & Pariah's Voam, Swedish techno wrangler Peder Mannerfelt injects a much-needed fruity freakiness to well worn tropes on his 10th year in this mode.
